<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-311-628  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 311 628.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  April 3 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fifth edition of The Computer Glossary has 4000+ entries. (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Endrijonas, Janet.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Computer Language Company (product introduction).andO;Product:   The Computer Glossary (Data base) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Software PublishersProduct IntroductionData basesSoftware packages.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>FIFTH EDITION OF THE COMPUTER GLOSSARY HAS 4000+ ENTRIES POINT PLEASANT,PENNSYLVANIA, U.S.A., 1990 MAR 22 (NB) -- The fifth edition of The ComputerGlossary, which also happens to be the first disk-based edition for hard diskPCs and Macintoshes, is on the way.andM;The PC version is expected to be released April 3 with the Mac versionfollowing in May. The cost of the latest edition is $59.95.andM;The Computer Glossary has been researched, written and edited by AlanFreedman, founder of The Computer Language Company, since 1980.andP;  While thefirst edition contained only 300 terms, this latest edition includes over4,000.andP;  Freedman says each of the 4,000 has been carefully researched toevaluate and determine its validity.andP;  Definitions for hundreds of softwarepackages and hardware models from micros to mainframes are included as is thelatest in &quot;Silicon Valley slang.&quot;andM;Terms defined cover personal computing, computer graphics, local areanetworking and desktop publishing and contains many charts.andP;  The diskrequires no printed documentation; installation and usage are defined inbrief instructions.andM;The PC version requires DOS 2.0 or higher and 256K (kilobytes) memory.andP;  Ittakes up less than 2 MB (megabytes) on a hard disk and can run stand-alone ormemory-resident in as little as 32K of memory.andM;The Macintosh version requires HyperCard version 1.2 or higher, 1 MB of RAM(random access memory) and takes less than 2 MB of hard disk space.andM;(Janet Endrijonas/19900327/Press Contact: The Computer Language Company,215-297-5999)</TEXT></DOC>